<h1>How to fight a medical bill</h1>

<p><em>Plus: Is your gas stove putting out benzene, too?</em></p>

</mj-text><mj-image width="500px" src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/BED4F991-6F90-40B6-96DD-57FB54F36254.png?w=1000" /><mj-text>

<p>Howdy, Colorado, we interrupt your compulsive refreshing of <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-us-canada-65967464">live updates on the hunt for the missing Titanic tourist submersible</a> to bring you this week&#8217;s edition of The Temperature, perhaps the only newsletter <em>not</em> looking for a local angle on this tragedy-in-the-making.</p>

<p>Times like this sure remind us of how history echoes â€” a grandiose voyage, marketed especially to the well-heeled; seemingly <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/06/21/us/titan-sub-safety-oceangate-employees/index.html">prescient safety concerns</a>, allegedly brushed aside; the unforgivingly brutal potential of the natural world on a planet that, though it is becoming more interconnected, still has quite a few remote spots.</p>

<p>It can be awfully easy to think that the bad things that are happening now exceed the bad things that happened previously â€” so much so that science has a name for it: &#8220;biased memory effect.&#8221; That&#8217;s why it was a strange comfort this month to read a new study in the journal Nature entitled <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06137-x">&#8220;The Illusion of Moral Decline.&#8221;</a></p>

<p>The gist is in the title: People think the past was more virtuous than the present, when, in fact, it&#8217;s always been bad. But that&#8217;s actually good news! Because it means that we, today, have just as much agency to fix things as our forebears did. Put another way, you may not always be able to avert disaster, but there <em>is</em> always an opportunity to make things better.</p>

<p>So let&#8217;s take that with us as we dig into today&#8217;s news.</p>

