</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">TEMP CHECK<br /><span style="font-size:12px;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:normal;"><em>The latest climate &amp; health reporting under The Sun</em></span></h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">HEALTH</h4>

<h2>How to fight your medical bills, according to the experts</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/diane-kruse-facility-fees-os-4-scaled.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>An itemized receipt sent to Conifer resident Kevin Kruse for a cardiology visits shows a hospital facility fee of about $135. (Olivia Sun, The Colorado Sun via Report for America)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;There's certainly no lack of people who need help with their medical bills.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>â€” Stephanie Arenales, director of the Colorado Consumer Health Initiative&#8217;s Consumer Assistance Program</em></span></blockquote>

<p>Yesterday marked the fifth anniversary for a program in Colorado that helps people battle insurers, hospitals and medical billers.</p>

<p>The nonprofit <strong>Colorado Consumer Health Initiative</strong>&#8217;s <strong>Consumer Assistance Program</strong> reports that it has helped more than 2,600 people during its lifespan, with a combined savings exceeding $7 million. And it&#8217;s really just getting started.</p>

<p>The program&#8217;s caseloads have increased 18% over the past year, said <strong>Stephanie Arenales</strong>, the program&#8217;s director. It hopes to expand this year with additional funding â€” there is <a target="_blank"  href="https://cohealthinitiative.org/events/2023-cap-gala/">a fundraising gala scheduled for tomorrow night in Denver</a>. But Arenales and CCHI executive director <strong>Mannat Singh</strong> say they know they will never be able to serve <em>everyone</em> in Colorado dealing with a complex health care bill. That&#8217;s why they label the program as a stopgap, while CCHI works on larger systemic reforms to make health care more affordable.</p>

<p>&#8220;There's certainly no lack of people who need help with their medical bills,&#8221; Arenales said.</p>

<p>So, we decided to ask Singh and Arenales, as well as program coordinator <strong>Melissa Duncan</strong>, for their top tips in fighting a big medical bill.</p>

<p><strong>Tip #1: Wait.</strong> When bills start rolling in, a lot of folks get an itch to just start paying them in order to leave the stress behind. But try to hold off instead until you are sure you have all the paperwork you need and all your questions resolved. Tell your insurer and health care provider that you are challenging the bill, and keep repeating that any time a bill collector calls. &#8220;The big thing is communication between all parties,&#8221; Duncan said.</p>

<p><strong>Tip #2: Gather.</strong> To fight a bill, you&#8217;ll probably need more than just the billing statement from the health care provider (or hospital) and the explanation of benefits from the insurer. You&#8217;ll want to make sure you have all the details on your insurance plan. Two documents are important here: the summary of benefits and coverage, which is usually a handful of pages and typically available through your insurer&#8217;s online portal; and the much bigger evidence of coverage, which you may have to call your insurer (or your employer, if it&#8217;s a health plan through work) to get.</p>

<p>Once you have those documents, you can start to compare whether your insurer correctly matched the charges to your specific coverage.</p>

<p>You may also need additional documents. If your insurer is denying coverage because it says something is not medically necessary, call your health care provider to get all the medical records you can â€” including doctors&#8217; notes and chart information. If you can show your insurer that your doctor thought certain care was medically necessary, that goes a long way.</p>

<p><strong>Tip #3: Learn.</strong> Readers of this newsletter know that health care policy is complicated. But it&#8217;s nothing compared to the health care billing process. This isn&#8217;t something you can just wing. You need to educate yourself on how it works.</p>

<p>CCHI has <a target="_blank"  href="https://cohealthinitiative.org/resources-for-consumers/">a variety of resources on its website</a> explaining the basics of health insurance and medical billing. You can also ask if your health care provider has a financial assistance program that you qualify for â€” this is especially important when it comes to hospital bills. Hospitals are required to tell uninsured patients about such programs, but insured patients may qualify, too, depending on income level.</p>

<p><strong>Tip #4: Complain.</strong> If you are at an impasse with your insurer or health care provider, you can try filing a complaint with a regulatory body. The <strong>Colorado Division of Insurance</strong> <a target="_blank"  href="https://doi.colorado.gov/for-consumers/file-a-complaint">handles complaints</a> against insurance plans that it regulates. The federal <strong>Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services</strong> <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.cms.gov/Regulations-and-Guidance/Administrative-Simplification/Enforcements/FileaComplaint">fields other complaints</a>, including some for people not covered by either Medicare or Medicaid. The state <strong>Division of Professions and Occupations</strong> may take others. Because it&#8217;s not easy to know what kind of complaint goes where, an assistance program like CCHI&#8217;s can be helpful in offering direction. Which leads us to â€¦</p>

<p><strong>Tip #5: Know when you&#8217;re in over your head.</strong> &#8220;It shouldn't take expertise to push back against health care bills,&#8221; Duncan said. But it does. So sometimes you need expert help. CCHI&#8217;s <a target="_blank"  href="https://cohealthinitiative.org/cap/">Consumer Assistance Program</a> is free of charge to consumers. Many times, it doesn&#8217;t need to launch into a full-blown attack to help a consumer resolve a bill but instead will give people a little guidance so they can help themselves. But, if it requires a monthslong campaign, they can help with that, too.</p>

<p>The caveat is that the program is staffed by only a handful of people and has capacity to handle about 100 cases at any one time. Cases are dealt with on a first-come, first-served basis.</p>

