<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">HEALTH</h4>

<h2>More clues in the great Centura naming mystery</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Screenshot-2023-06-19-at-6.26.08-PM.jpg?w=800" href="https://networkofcare.adventhealth.com/colorado" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>A screenshot of a website set up by AdventHealth announcing that the system's five Denver metro area hospitals will soon carry the AdventHealth name instead of the Centura name. Click the image to be taken to the website. (John Ingold, The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">5</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">The number of hospitals currently carrying the Centura name that will soon operate under the AdventHealth name</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>Regular readers know that we are <em>obsessed</em> with one relatively trivial question from the biggest Colorado health system crackup in years: What the heck is going to happen to the <strong>Centura Health</strong> name once the company dissolves?</p>

<p>The background: Centura was formed in 1996, and is a partnership between Catholic-affiliated <strong>CommonSpirit Health</strong> and Seventh Day Adventist-affiliated <strong>AdventHealth</strong>. On Valentine&#8217;s Day this year, the companies <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/02/14/centura-health-breakup-commonspriti-adventhealth/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">announced their divorce</a>, which they say should be done by the end of next month.</p>

<p>But, meanwhile, Centura kept making moves. It acquired a chain of hospitals in Utah and then scooped rival UCHealth to become the official health care partner of the Denver Broncos â€” a deal that put Centura&#8217;s name on the team&#8217;s training facility.</p>

<p>That suggested the Centura name wasn&#8217;t going away. But who would own it? Which hospitals would continue operating under it? The company wouldn&#8217;t say. (And still won&#8217;t â€” a Centura spokeswoman responded to a request for comment with a statement saying, &#8220;At this time, there are no further details to share.&#8221;)</p>

<p>But two recent announcements provide more evidence that the CommonSpirit hospitals â€” including the flagship <strong>St. Anthony Hospital</strong> in Lakewood â€” may continue operating under the Centura name while the AdventHealth hospitals will not.</p>

<p>The first clue came late last month, when it was announced that hospital industry veteran <strong>Jim Sheets</strong> <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.centura.org/news/jim-sheets-named-group-president-multi-state-health-system-based-centennial">would become group president</a> covering hospitals in Colorado and Utah. The news release was sent out under the Centura banner, but it also noted that Sheets&#8217; would only be responsible for the Centura hospitals owned by CommonSpirit.</p>

<p>The second clue hit more recently, when the five Adventist hospitals in Colorado â€” <strong>Avista Adventist Hospital</strong> in Louisville, <strong>Castle Rock Adventist Hospital</strong>, <strong>Littleton Adventist Hospital</strong>, <strong>Parker Adventist Hospital</strong> and <strong>Porter Adventist Hospital</strong> in Denver â€” began running ads noting that they <a target="_blank"  href="https://networkofcare.adventhealth.com/colorado">&#8220;will soon be part of the AdventHealth network of care.&#8221;</a></p>

<p>Those hospitals&#8217; websites remain tied to Centura&#8217;s â€” and a search for them on AdventHealth&#8217;s care finder tool still redirects to the Centura sites. But the ads are the first confirmation that at least <em>some</em> of the hospitals are about to undergo a name change.</p>

