<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">MORE HEALTH NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><strong>A new family therapy program in Colorado will meet you wherever you are â€” even if that&#8217;s Costco. </strong>&gt;&gt; Over the past decade, Colorado has made a U-turn in how it handles treatment for troubled youth. The state is sending fewer kids to institutions and putting more resources toward at-home care. But what does that look like on the ground? Tag along with Sun journalists <strong>Jennifer Brown</strong> and <strong>Olivia Sun</strong> as they sit in on one such therapy session. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/15/home-therapy-colorado-teens-mental-health/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>A hidden loneliness epidemic endangers Coloradans, especially older adults. </strong>&gt;&gt; Even before the COVID pandemic hit, nearly half of U.S. adults reported feeling lonely. And the health impacts of that loneliness epidemic are real â€” isolation brings with it greater risk of dementia, cardiovascular disease, depression and premature death. But, as <strong>Claire Cleveland</strong> reports, one program in Colorado is trying to build connections between seniors. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/15/loneliness-isolation-health-risks-colorado-solutions/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Trust</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>When Silicon Valley-style business strategies tried to disrupt health insurance, it didn&#8217;t go super-well. </strong>&gt;&gt; <strong>Friday Health Plans</strong>, which recently announced that it is going out of business, is the latest so-called &#8220;insurtech&#8221; company to see its bubble burst both in Colorado and nationally. Why does this keep happening? Because it turns out that you need more than low premium prices backed by a boatload of venture capital money to make it as a health insurer. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/20/friday-health-plans-insurance-insurtech/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Massage therapists ease the pain of hospice patients, but they aren&#8217;t easy to find. </strong>&gt;&gt; Fewer than 1% of massage therapists specialize in hospice or palliative care. That makes it difficult to provide massage care to patients nearing the end of their life, even though massage is a top request from patients and their families. But for those massage therapists who work in the field, the emotional rewards are immense. &#8220;When you&#8217;re dying and somebody touches you without expectation of anything in return, you just get to be,&#8221; one told reporter <strong>Kate Ruder</strong>. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/17/massage-therapy-hospice-palliative-care/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>KFF Health News</strong></a></li>
</ul>

