<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">CLIMATE</h4>

<h2>Yes, you can still trade for a clean lawnmower</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/lawn-electric-e-equipment-os-4.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Kirsten Schatz, advocate for the Colorado Public Interest Research Group, or CoPIRG, speaks Dec. 1 near Sloan&#8217;s Lake in support of cleaner air quality through the restriction of sales of gas-powered landscaping equipment. (Olivia Sun, The Colorado Sun via Report for America)</em></span></p>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">$250,000</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Electric lawn equipment vouchers available from the RAQC this year</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>Now that the sun is out and your grass is growing like mad, it&#8217;s a good time to answer a <strong>reader's question</strong> about getting one of those nearly free <strong>clean electric lawnmowers</strong>.</p>

<p>Yes,<strong> Regional Air Quality Council</strong> officials say, there&#8217;s still money in the pot for those who want to cut into Colorado&#8217;s ozone problem by trading a dirty burner for a voucher. The voucher program makes some of the well-reviewed electric models free or extremely affordable.</p>

<p>RAQC&#8217;s <strong>Mow Down Pollution</strong> has $250,000 to spend on vouchers this season, up from $100,000 last year. As of June 16, about $136,000 had been redeemed in vouchers, said RAQC&#8217;s <strong>David Sabados</strong>. Looming Disappointment Warning: At least $215,000 might already be committed, Sabados cautioned. Consumers have a limited time to spend the vouchers they get, and the gap to $136,000 includes those given out that hadn&#8217;t been redeemed yet.</p>

<p>Why do they do it, you ask? A reminder here that Colorado&#8217;s northern Front Range counties have serious problems with ground-level toxic <strong>ozone</strong>, which is created by a combination of fossil fuel emissions, wildfire smoke, volatile organic compounds and hot summer sun.</p>

<p>Lawn care equipment makes up a surprising chunk of the ozone problem because two-cycle engines run dirty. Trading in enough gas equipment for rechargeable or plug-in electric could trim a couple of parts per billion off ozone levels the EPA rules currently cap at 70 ppb.</p>

<p>Mow Down Pollution provides:</p>

<ul><li>$75 voucher for handheld electric equipment (like a grass trimmer): Recycling of a gas handheld item is mandatory.</li>

<li>$75 voucher for an electric lawn mower if no gas mower is being turned in.</li>

<li>$150 voucher for electric lawn mower if recycling a gas mower.</li>
</ul>

<p>Read a longer update on the voucher program next week at ColoradoSun.com. In the meantime, learn more and seek your voucher<a target="_blank"  href="https://www.mowdownpollution.org/residential-2022/"> here at the RAQC website</a>. They will be gone before long, so get them while you can.</p>

