<mj-text>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">MORE ENVIRONMENT NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><strong>Should Colorado give up early on a looming ozone downgrade? </strong>&gt;&gt; Colorado&#8217;s northern Front Range counties have already passed the threshold for this year that requires the EPA to downgrade us to &#8220;serious&#8221; violations of 2015 ozone standards, environmental groups say. They want state air pollution officials to go ahead and call it now, ahead of deadlines, in order to get started sooner on potential ozone fixes. The state says it is actually considering the idea, knowing the numbers are bad, <strong>Michael Booth</strong> reports. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/19/colorado-ozone-violations-2023-epa-sanctions/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>West Coast wildfires do indeed make Colorado&#8217;s ozone problem much worse, study shows. </strong>&gt;&gt; Smoke from distant West Coast fires contributes a significant part of Colorado&#8217;s Front Range ozone problem in summer months, according to a new study by NOAA and CU Boulder scientists. The results from the awful 2021 ozone season may have big implications for state regulators, who have to balance EPA demands to cut ozone with resistance from industries who say new rules will hurt their business, <strong>Michael Booth</strong> reports. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/20/wildfire-smoke-colorado-ozone-study/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Blue Mesa is filling back up, and the proof is in these slider photos. </strong>&gt;&gt; The drought has been abusing poor Blue Mesa Reservoir for years, draining it down to the bare bones river track in the middle of a dry lake. But <strong>William Woody&#8217;s </strong>cool slider comparison of then-and-now photos shows how much a great snowpack and rainy season can fill up a key body of water. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/16/blue-mesa-water-level-photos-2021-2023/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>The warehouse boom may claim a quiet, beloved Jeffco lake neighborhood. </strong>&gt;&gt; Every box placed conveniently on your doorstep started at a series of warehouses, and any drive around metro Denver shows the enormous boom in newly built warehouse space. <strong>Jennifer Brown</strong> writes about a quiet lake in Jefferson County where the neighbors who love to walk may find themselves confronting a new warehouse district across the water. They are not happy. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/06/19/warehouses-jefferson-county-arvada-hyatt-lake/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>
</ul>

</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">CHART OF THE WEEK</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h2>Colorado&#8217;s falling COVID hospitalizations</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Hospital.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>This chart shows trends in the number of people hospitalized with COVID-19 infections from the start of the pandemic through the week of June 13, 2023. (Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment)</em></span></p>

<p>In news <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.cpr.org/2023/06/16/colorado-covid-hospitalizations-june-2023/">first reported last week</a> by <strong>Colorado Public Radio</strong>&#8217;s <strong>John Daley</strong>, the number of people hospitalized with COVID-19 is the smallest in Colorado since the start of the pandemic. (This includes the very first week in March 2020 when the state began tracking COVID hospitalizations.)</p>

<p>As of last week&#8217;s tally, there were 64 people hospitalized with a case of COVID. About two-thirds of those are hospitalized because of the consequences of the disease â€” as opposed to being hospitalized for another reason and happening to have a COVID infection. That proportion is roughly in line with previous weeks&#8217;.</p>

<p>Updated numbers should be released this afternoon, so be sure to check the <strong>Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment</strong>&#8217;s COVID-19 <a target="_blank"  href="https://covid19.colorado.gov/data">data dashboard</a> to see if the trend continues.</p>

